II. OVERVIEW OF TEXTUAL ADVERSARIAL ATTACK
A. Related Work on Sentence-level Attack (Done)
Sentence-level adversarial attacks manipulate entire sentences or phrases to mislead NLP models, thereby altering their outputs or guiding them toward incorrect predictions. These attacks often exploit strategies designed to confuse models, rendering them unable to process the input text correctly. For instance, Lin [47] revealed statistical biases in machine reading comprehension models, showing a tendency to favor irrelevant options over true understanding. Similarly focused on model vulnerabilities, Xu [48] proposed a grey-box framework for sentiment classification, using Gumbel-softmax and competitive objectives to generate high-quality adversarial examples. Generation techniques have also advanced: SynPG [49] presented syntax-controlled generation through semantic syntactic disentanglement, enhancing diversity without annotated data, while CAT-Gen [50] developed a model that generates diverse adversarial texts through precise control over task-irrelevant attributes, thereby improving output diversity and attack robustness. Ensuring semantic integrity, T3 implemented target-controllable attacks through tree-structured
