B. Related Work on Word-level Attack
Word-level adversarial attacks, which modify individual words to deceive NLP models while preserving text meaning and grammar, exploit model vulnerabilities through subtle, often human-imperceptible changes. For instance, Gumbel Attack [60] optimizes objectives via parameterized distributions and the Gumbel trick, aiming to reduce or eliminate the need for model evaluation during attacks (a challenge also addressed by methods like Seq2Sick for sequence models [61]). This approach also categorized attacks into non-overlapping and targeted keyword types using distinct loss functions for seq2seq models. Another approach, QA-Attack [62], combines the attention mechanism with a deletion ranking method to execute successful word-level adversarial attacks in questionanswering models while maintaining semantic consistency. TEXTFLOLER [63] introduced a two-stage framework that ranks words by impact and then replaces them under semantic and grammatical constraints. Reinforcement learning has also been employed, for example, by Zou et al. [64], to iteratively degrade model performance in neural machine translation. Focusing on linguistic realism, grammar-based attacks simulating natural language errors such as typos and incorrect verb forms were developed by Yin et al. [65], while MORPHEUS [66] was proposed to perturb inflectional forms to uncover model biases and improve robustness. To test specific model capabilities, Shi et al. [67] modified shared vocabulary in sentence pairs for paraphrase identification models. Separately, Emelin et al. [68] introduced ’attractive vocabulary’
