C. Related Work on Char-level Attack (Done)
Character-level adversarial attacks manipulate individual characters to disrupt text meaning and deceive NLP models [32]. Early demonstrations of vulnerability involved introducing natural and synthetic noise, such as spelling mistakes and character shuffling, to character-based NMT models [74]. More targeted methods have since emerged. For example, VertAttack [75] was proposed as an adversarial method targeting text classifiers through vertical keyword rewriting, bypassing horizontal text processing mechanisms to induce significant accuracy degradation while preserving high human comprehension rates. Ebrahimi et al. [33] advanced letter-edit operations through vector representation and gradient estimation, employing strategies like one-shot, greedy algorithms, and beam search to optimize character replacements and significantly degrade translation quality. Similarly, Charmer [76], an efficient query-based character-level attack, generates highly similar adversarial examples with high success rates, effectively targeting models including BERT and Llama 2. Blackbox approaches have also been developed; Gao et al. [77] proposed a method selecting words for modification based on model responses to word removal, achieving notable reductions in classification accuracy. In other investigations, Rocamora et al. [76] leveraged Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting techniques combined with character-level substitutions to investigate AraBERT model robustness, revealing that finetuned models exhibit greater resilience than original architectures. To enhance black-box attack efficiency, Gil et al. [78] employed LSTM networks to emulate white-box attacks without compromising success rates. Beyond typical character edits, Eger et al. [79] introduced a visual perturbator that swaps characters with visually similar counterparts, effectively evading sensitive word detection models through glyph-based substitution. Punctuation manipulations also prove effective: Du et al. [80] developed punctuation-level attacks combined with TPPE/TPPEP embedding search methods to systematically probe text model vulnerability to punctuation perturbations, demonstrating that single-punctuation modifications can deceive models while preserving human readability. Correspondingly, Formento et al. [81] explored punctuation insertion
as an adversarial strategy, showing its superior performance over traditional character-level attacks like TextFooler [82] and SememePSO [83] in maintaining semantic similarity and readability. These diverse techniques highlight the significant vulnerabilities of NLP models to subtle character manipulations and underscore the critical need for robust defenses.
III. OVERVIEW OF TEXTUAL MODEL DEFENSE
In the rapidly evolving domains of network security and NLP, safeguarding text models against adversarial attacks has become paramount. Adversarial attacks, which involve meticulously engineered inputs, pose significant threats to model resilience and security [25]. These attacks are often categorized based on the attacker’s knowledge of the target model and the granularity of linguistic operations involved [84]. To counter such threats, a comprehensive defense framework has emerged, encompassing diverse strategies to enhance model robustness. The first line of this defense involves detection and identification techniques; leveraging heuristics, statistical analysis, and anomaly detection, these methods flag adversarial inputs by identifying deviations from expected linguistic patterns [27], [28], serving as a foundational layer for targeted mitigation. Building on detection, adversarial training and mitigation strategies constitute the second pillar, fortifying NLP models by exposing them to crafted adversarial examples during training. This exposure enhances generalization and resistance to manipulation [39]. Post-training techniques, such as gradient masking and input sanitization, further bolster this resilience by reducing susceptibility to known attack patterns [46]. A third crucial aspect of defense focuses on enhancing semantic and contextual understanding. Techniques like semantic knowledge graphs, contextual embeddings, and syntactic analysis help models differentiate legitimate inputs from adversarial ones; integrating such deep semantic understanding, often during the training phase, significantly improves overall model resilience [11], [85]. Finally, general enhancements such as ensemble methods, regularization techniques, and hybrid approaches provide supplementary protection, forming the fourth component of this framework [41], [42]. These strategies aim to address gaps left by more specific defenses, thereby offering additional layers of robustness. Together, these four pillars—detection, adversarial training, semantic analysis, and general enhancements—form a cohesive defense framework that advances the state of the art in text model security [26], [45], [86]. By integrating these multifaceted strategies, researchers can strive to develop resilient NLP systems capable of withstanding the increasingly sophisticated tactics employed in adversarial attacks.
A. Related Work on Detection and Identification (Done)
In the realm of detecting and identifying word-level adversarial text attacks, several innovative methods have emerged to bolster the security of natural language processing (NLP) systems. For instance, Shapley Additive Explanations [87] has been employed to efficiently pinpoint subtle, potentially malicious perturbations within text data, directly aiding in
