nal in the ongoing effort to secure NLP systems against word-level adversarial text attacks.
B. Related Work on Adversarial Training and Mitigation (Done)
In the realm of adversarial training and mitigation for text models, several notable approaches have emerged to enhance their resilience. The Textual Manifold-based Defense (TMD) [96], for instance, stands out with its two-step process combining language model fine-tuning with InfoGAN training, promising robust defence against adversarial attacks. SHIELD [97] offers versatility by focusing on bolstering model accuracy against black-box adversarial attacks. Emphasizing symbolic perturbations, Discrete Adversarial Training (DAT) [98] introduces a novel method to enhance model robustness. For specific attack vectors, Dirichlet Neighborhood Ensemble (DNE) [99] effectively addresses attacks relying on synonym substitutions. Further specialized techniques include Manifold Adversarial Augmentation (MAA) [100] for enhancing Neural Machine Translation (NMT) model robustness, and the Fast Gradient Projection Method (FGPM) [27] which offers an efficient defence against synonym substitution attacks. Broadening the scope, Character-Level Adversarial Training [101] adds another layer of security, while Robust Adversarial
Training for Machine Reading Comprehension (MRC) [102] is tailored for MRC models. The FreeLB method [103] also leverages adversarial training to enhance the robustness and performance of language understanding models. Beyond these direct training modifications, other paradigms contribute significantly: dynamic red-teaming methodologies [104] highlight the role of human-model adversarial interactions in generating realistic attack patterns for more effective training. Prompt Adversarial Tuning [105] introduces a learnable guard-prefix to user prompts, jointly optimized against both adversarial and benign scenarios to achieve robust refusal behavior. Furthermore, offering provable guarantees, Erase-and-check [106] presents a certifiable defense based on token erasure, providing safety assurances under bounded adversarial modifications. These diverse strategies collectively underscore the promising directions in fortifying text models against adversarial threats.
C. Related Work on General Enhancement and Miscellaneous (Done)
In the realm of general enhancement and miscellaneous strategies for text model defence, a range of innovative approaches has emerged. Adversarial and Mixup Data Augmentation [107], for instance, stands as a fundamental technique for bolstering model robustness through data augmentation. BERT-Defense [108] demonstrates proficiency in countering orthographic adversarial attacks using BERT’s probabilistic model, a valuable asset in mitigating such threats. The ADFAR Framework [109] further contributes to the defense arsenal by effectively combatting adversarial word substitution attacks. Concurrently, Frequency-Guided Word Substitutions (FGWS) [110] offer an efficient means to identify adversarial examples in NLP tasks based on word frequency properties. Robust Encodings (RobEn) [111] address adversarial typos without altering model architecture, while Iterative Training for Dialogue Safety [112] tackles the vital challenge of enhancing dialogue system resilience. Additionally, base-inflexion encoding [113] focuses on improving NLP accuracy for non-standard English dialects, thereby promoting inclusivity and accessibility in defended systems. Finally, in this group of established techniques, Robust Adversarial Augmentation (RAA) [114] holds promise in enhancing model robustness and generalization through high-level hidden representations. More recent advancements introduce sophisticated frameworks and LLM-specific defenses. AegisLLM [115], for example, introduces a cooperative multi-agent framework for realtime defence against adversarial attacks without retraining, leveraging agentic optimization and inference-time adaptability. Understanding LLM capabilities in security also informs defense development, as highlighted by an empirical study from Shao et al. [116] evaluating LLMs’ ability to solve cybersecurity Capture-The-Flag (CTF) challenges and benchmarking their automated problem-solving. Directly addressing online threats, AEGIS [117] presents an online adaptive content moderation system using an ensemble of LLM experts to enhance safety robustness dynamically. Comprehensive toolkits are also emerging; AISafetyLab [118] offers an integrated framework with attack, defence, and evaluation modules for
