V. RELATED WORK ON DATASET (DONE)
Steffen Eger et al. [124] highlight the lack of realism in prevailing research scenarios compared to real-world applications like social networks, instead focusing on low-level role-based attacks that leverage human cognitive robustness and presenting a benchmark of nine distinct attack patterns to evaluate future NLP model resilience. Further highlighting evaluation challenges, Ailem et al. [125] have shown that performance correlations among prompts in major benchmarks are non-random, significantly impacting model rankings and calling for robustness checks that account for different distributional assumptions in LLM evaluations. To address such benchmark limitations, Dynabench was introduced by Kiela et al. [126] to intertwine dataset creation, model development, and evaluation, thereby tackling the tendency of models to excel on static benchmarks while faltering in real-world tasks. This vulnerability of evaluation systems is further underscored by findings from Raina et al. [127] that short universal adversarial phrases can mislead judge-LLMs in zero-shot evaluation settings, causing them to inflate scores—a critical issue demanding redesigned, robust evaluation systems. The development of dynamic benchmarks, such as the NLI dataset by Nie et al. [128] collected through adversarial human-model interactions, aims to align with endless learning principles and avoid static test saturation. Extending this focus on dynamic and real-world challenges, the PowerPoint Task Completion-Robustness (PPTC-R) benchmark [129] evaluates large language models’ ability to handle adversarial instructions across linguistic and software version changes, revealing systemic weaknesses in current models. Addressing dataset quality directly, Gardner et al. [130] introduced contrast sets to counter systematic dataset gaps that lead to misleading evaluations, proposing a rigorous annotation paradigm to ensure models capture intended capabilities rather than simplistic decision rules. Together, these works emphasize the critical need for realistic, dynamic, and comprehensive evaluation frameworks to truly advance the robustness and reliability of NLP models. Complementing these efforts, JailbreakBench serves as an evolving open-source framework for jailbreaking
attack and defense research, featuring standardized evaluation metrics and a behavior dataset to enhance security-focused benchmarking [131]–[135]. In parallel, RUPBench [136] provides a comprehensive robustness evaluation across 15 reasoning datasets and nine types of textual perturbations, uncovering both model-sizedependent robustness patterns and persistent error types that call for architectural improvements. The critical role of data in these advanced evaluations is underscored by Gao et al. [137], who stress that high-quality annotated data remains vital for fine-tuning NLG evaluation models, particularly as LLMs expand task scenarios into instruction-response paradigms. However, as highlighted by Wu et al. [138], current limitations in dataset volume, complexity, and resource-intensive curation processes present major bottlenecks for developing effective detectors and evaluation metrics—challenges that demand innovative approaches to data resource design.
VI. DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSION
The rapid advancement of large language models (LLMs) has revolutionized natural language processing but has simultaneously exposed their vulnerability to sophisticated adversarial attacks, which pose significant risks to their reliability and security. This survey has provided a comprehensive review of textual adversarial attacks and defense mechanisms, categorizing attacks into sentence-, word-, and character-level manipulations, and detailing key defense strategies including detection, adversarial training, semantic analysis, and general system enhancements. The concept of certified robustness, which offers formal guarantees of model resilience, was also highlighted as a particularly promising avenue. Despite notable progress in understanding and mitigating these threats, substantial challenges persist concerning real-world applicability, scalability, generalization across diverse models and attack types, and the establishment of standardized benchmarking. As adversarial threats continue to evolve in complexity and subtlety, ongoing, focused research is crucial for the development of truly secure, reliable, and robust language models. This survey aims to serve as a valuable resource in this endeavor, fostering the creation of resilient NLP systems capable of withstanding increasingly sophisticated adversarial tactics.
